RADIOLOGY REPORT - Chest X-Ray
Study ID:IM-0352
Case ID:CXR-TRAIN-IM-0352
Modality:Chest X-Ray (PA)
Report Date:December 17, 2025

I. Findings

Lungs:
  • The heart size is within normal limits.
  • The mediastinum is unremarkable.
  • The bony structures of the rib cage are intact.
Pleura:
  • No pleural effusion is identified.
  • No pneumothorax is identified.
Heart and Mediastinum:
  • The heart size is within normal limits.
  • The mediastinal contours are unremarkable.
  • The trachea is midline.
Bones:
  • The ribs appear intact.
  • The clavicles are intact.
  • The scapulae are intact.
Upper Abdomen:
  • The upper abdomen is unremarkable. No free air is seen under the diaphragm.

II. Signs of Pneumonia or Other Pathology

  • There are no obvious signs of pneumonia, such as consolidation or infiltrates.
  • No other significant abnormalities are identified.

III. Impression

Impression: Normal chest X-ray. No evidence of pneumonia, pleural effusion, pneumothorax, or other significant pathology.

IV. Differential Diagnosis

  • If the patient presents with symptoms suggestive of pneumonia, further evaluation with a CT scan of the chest may be warranted to rule out subtle findings not visible on a standard chest X-ray.
  • If the patient presents with symptoms suggestive of a pleural effusion, a repeat chest X-ray or a CT scan of the chest may be warranted.
  • If the patient presents with symptoms suggestive of a pneumothorax, a repeat chest X-ray or a CT scan of the chest may be warranted.

Case ID:CXR-TRAIN-IM-0162
Modality:Chest X-Ray (PA)
Report Date:December 17, 2025

I. Findings

Lungs:
  • The lungs appear clear bilaterally, without evidence of consolidation, pleural effusion, or pneumothorax.
  • The heart size appears normal.
  • The mediastinal contours are unremarkable.
Pleura:
  • No pleural effusion is identified.
  • No pneumothorax is identified.
Heart and Mediastinum:
  • The heart size is within normal limits.
  • The mediastinal contours are normal.
  • The hila are unremarkable.
Bones:
  • The visualized bony structures (ribs, clavicles, scapulae, and upper thoracic spine) appear intact without evidence of fractures.
  • The vertebral bodies are intact.
Upper Abdomen:
  • The upper abdomen is unremarkable.

II. Signs of Pneumonia or Other Pathology

  • No evidence of pneumonia is identified.
  • No other significant pathology is apparent on this single view.

III. Impression

Impression: Normal chest X-ray.
Differential Diagnosis:
  • If the patient has symptoms suggestive of pneumonia, further evaluation with a lateral decubitus X-ray or CT scan of the chest may be warranted to rule out subtle findings.
  • If the patient has symptoms suggestive of a cardiac abnormality, further evaluation with echocardiography may be warranted.
  • If the patient has symptoms suggestive of a skeletal abnormality, further evaluation with dedicated skeletal imaging may be warranted.

RADIOLOGY REPORT - Chest X-Ray
Study ID:IM-0291
Case ID:CXR-TRAIN-IM-0291
Modality:Chest X-Ray (PA)
Report Date:December 17, 2025
I. Study Description:
  • Single frontal chest radiograph.
II. Findings:
Lungs:
  • The lungs appear clear bilaterally without evidence of consolidation, pleural effusion, or pneumothorax.
Pleura:
  • The costophrenic angles are sharp. No pleural effusion is identified.
Heart and Mediastinum:
  • The heart size is within normal limits.
  • The mediastinal contours are unremarkable.
  • The trachea is midline.
Bones:
  • The visualized bony structures (ribs, clavicles, scapulae) appear intact.
Upper Abdomen:
  • The upper abdomen is not well visualized due to the patient's body habitus.
III. Signs of Pneumonia or Other Pathology:
  • No evidence of pneumonia is identified.
  • No other significant abnormalities are apparent.
IV. Impression:
  • The chest X-ray is unremarkable.
Diagnosis/Differential:
  • No acute cardiopulmonary pathology identified.
  • Differential diagnosis includes:
  • Normal chest X-ray.
  • Early or subtle pneumonia (requires further evaluation if clinical suspicion is high).
  • Other less common conditions (e.g., congenital abnormalities, masses) - further imaging may be needed if clinically indicated.
V. Recommendations:
  • Clinical correlation is recommended.
  • If clinical suspicion for pneumonia persists, consider further imaging (e.g., CT scan of the chest) or repeat chest X-ray in 1-2 weeks.
